Perspectives for Sino-American Relations in 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations unsettled large parts of Asia.
A year earlier, U.S. President Donald Trump returned from his particularly lavish "State Visit Plus" to Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-China campaign rhetoric would finally become a thing of the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are entangled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the U.S. "strategic engagement" in China with "strategic competition."
Adding to this is the fact that the U.S., European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
There is great uncertainty in the financial markets today, with growth slowing in China and Europe and higher interest rates starting to take effect in America.
The uncertainty about the future development of the nuclear talks with North Korea also dims the picture.
So what are the prospects for U.S.-China relations in 2019?
It is likely that by March there will be an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions China will make in this regard.
An agreement on tariff cuts is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If tariffs were negotiated one after another, a year could pass.
If Chinese economic reformers, however, adopt a more drastic approach by gradually committing to the abolition of all tariffs and asking Americans to do the same, a faster result could be achieved.
This would, however, contradict Chinese trade officials who have been trained over decades to give little, let alone everything, all at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Nonetheless, reform is something different from the way contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there are no specific provisions regarding technology transfer.
The protection of intellectual property is however extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the administration of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed again.
Enforcement or legal action in cases of violations of intellectual property rights remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism is to subject relevant agreements between Chinese and foreign companies to international arbitration systems based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically entrusted with the enforcement of intellectual property protection.
If China raises objections, it could develop its own international trade arbitration process based in China.
For this, China would need to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration body in order to strengthen its international credibility.
No one has trust in Chinese trade courts.
To meet its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent trade and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal courts will remain under political control.
American concerns regarding state subsidies under China's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be resolved.
The fact is that all countries provide a certain degree of state support to their domestic technology sectors, although this is highest in China.
Even if we prescribed a maximum level of state support for a particular company, it would be difficult to assess whether compliance is achieved.
I am not confident that there will be an agreement in this area.
Perhaps America simply has to outmaneuver China by increasing public investment in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China may offer tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
China might eventually decide to take the drastic step of agreeing to tariff-free arrangements not only with the United States, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would present itself with a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to curb the trend toward protectionism.
As part of such a shift, China could request membership from the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP), in order to outmaneuver the United States (which had withdrawn from the free trade agreement as one of Trump's first official actions) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political opening and market access.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations regarding China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the United States, China is likely to be striving in its general foreign and security policy in 2019 to resolve conflicts in its relations with other countries.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from Japan's coast guard indicate a significant reduction in Chinese incursions into the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands area in the East China Sea.
China also aims to reduce tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea by accelerating the negotiation of a "Code of Conduct."
Furthermore, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China may begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, considering the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports Taiwanese independence, in the recent local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the United States continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the United States in the South China Sea continue to occur, and the conflict could escalate if the United States more clearly emphasizes its stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Across all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project, the "New Silk Road."
In recent months, however, the initiative has generated less political fanfare in China.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota Port to China, which triggered negative reactions and raised concerns regarding the long-term financial viability of the New Silk Road.
In 2019, triumphant reports on the New Silk Road are likely to be less frequent.
Furthermore, China is expected to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It is likely to continue appearing as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
More cautious representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially if the United States consistently shows contempt for them.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the United States and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership is likely to use the year 2019 to form a well-informed judgment about the future of U.S. policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new U.S. strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that the U.S. stance toward China has changed profoundly, they are still uncertain about the exact form this change will take and whether a fundamental shift in strategy (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
